r=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tanare>Tanare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/14/03 8:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Well that was unexpected</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought to herself as the last magical vestages from &quot;Jindrun'Beldol's&quot; gateway faded away. Even with the mask Kyri knew whose face lay behind it which confirmed her own suspicisions that Maelgroth was indeed one of the Waes'Harventhar. She sensed something when her &quot;uncle&quot; greeted him upon his arrival, some whispered conversation with meaning to only the two of them no doubt. Of course, as expected, Nystyre briefly looked towards her in case she did not recognize Maelgroth herself.<br>
<br>
   Mingling for a bit with the noblity to not be too obvious in her actions, a chore to be sure dealing with generally empty headed nobles who thought that mere birth granted greatness.<br>
 The matron of the Chath’elg’Caress was another reason why Kyri was glad she was not nobly born. As if a marriage bond interested her in the slightest, unless of course a great deal of platinum was involved. Kyri briefly felt bad for those noble daughters forced to wed because of some alliance or deal necessitated it. Soon enough she watched as the matron went to maelgroth next before the sounds of luaghter drove her from the field so to speak.<br>
<br>
   When the time came, Kyri decided to make her way to Maelgroth and discuss things. She knew he saw her for their eyes locked briefly as she watched the masked stranger  holding court with the member of house Ragar’Golhyrr. Soon after he went to see the lady Athava and chatted briefly which seemed to Kyri to have done well for Maelgroth left the guest of honor in a much better mood than when he first greeted her. Seeing him prepare to leave Kyri slipped out another way to meet him outside for a chance to speak privately. The time for comparing notes seemed to be right.<br>
<br>
  He saw her, she knew he did but oddly he appeared uncomfortable as she drew near. Before she could speak he vanished. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>What spooked him?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> she thought, knowing that her mere presence shouldn't have done so. It was one thing to have people say someone was intimidated by another's beauty but this was a bit much. With Maelgroth gone, Kyri knew she had best return inside before she was noticed to be missing.<br>
<br>
  Back inside she caught her &quot;uncle's&quot; eye and the two of them stepped out into another room briefly.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Well, what did you discover?&quot; Nystyre asked<br>
<br>
  &quot;Nothing actually.&quot; Kyri replied &quot;I managed to find him alone but as i came near to speak with him he used his magic to vanish to who knows where. I didn't have a chance to say a thing.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Hmm, that's very odd. This one did not seem the type to flee at the sight of a woman if he is indeed what he claims to be.&quot; Nystyre said. &quot;Well then if he is gone you may as well make some use of yourself the rest of the night and see what the other houses are up to since you scared off your main objective. But come 'neice' our guests are surely missing us by now.&quot;<br>
<br>
  Taking his arm, the two of them returned to the main hall. As Nystyre went back to his own duties Kyri found herself the sole remaining novelty of the event with Maelgroth having left. Several old women of various houses couldn't believe they had not heard of a branch of the D'vir clan in Mistmoore. The young men were even more attentive at her arrival, though most failed to raise their eyes above chest level when speaking to her, until she grabbed one from the Chath'elg'caress - perhaps the same one the matron spoke of earlier, by the hair and raised his eyes to hers while smiling sweetly with a cold glint in her eyes and saying &quot;When someone won't look me in the eye when speaking to me, I find it rather insulting. I would be happy to show you some of the techniques Mayong Mistmoore taught me to deal with insults if you continue this.&quot;<br>
<br>
   At the mention of the dark power of Mistmoore, the Chath'elg'caress's eyes grew wide as he stammered an apology and promptly thought of somewhere else he had to be. For some reason after this, the rest of the young men around her had pressing business to take care of as well and the crowd around her dispersed. To be sure some of the older noblemen smiled upon hearing the comment- the youth of today DID need to be shaken in their belief of their own superiority every now and then. This neice of Nystyre's seemed to be doing the job quite well.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Perhaps I should ask your uncle to lend you to my house for a time. You seem to be routing the Chath'elg'caress fairly well tonight.&quot; Ayon'daro stated as he drew close.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Well, to be honest they don't seem to be much of a challenge. I'm surprised they have risen as high as they have if this is the best they can muster.&quot; Kyri replied.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Yes, the old witch is on her way out I hear. You'd best be careful here Lady K'yari, its been said hired knives are cutting down many of the noblity. After tonight you may have an enemy or two.&quot; Ayon'daro warned<br>
<br>
  &quot;Hired knifes? My uncle's estates here are well defended. It would take a truly skilled killer to break in, and those would be expensive.&quot; Kyri answered.<br>
<br>
  Smiling Ayon'daro teased &quot;Oh really? What would someone so far away from the politics of Neriak know of the hiring of killers and their fees.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Cursing to herself at her slip Kyri quickly answered &quot;Well how else could a lone outpost in the middle of the weak elf lands stand? Military leaders need to be removed, strong rulers slain. Just because we are isolated does not mean we are ignorant my Lord Aton'daro.&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;True enough,&quot; Ayon'daro admitted, &quot;It must be terrible being stranded out there so far from court. Perhaps you could convince your uncle to let you stay here a time. You'll find things are much more interesting here.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Perhaps, we shall see.&quot; Kyri said, then changing the subject. &quot;My Lord, what did you think of that stranger with the mask, a most mysterious sort he seemed to me, and vanished just as quickly as he arrived. When I saw his arrival I almost thought this was to be a costume party and me without my mask.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Chuckling Ayon'daro said, &quot;That one is an odd one, if I could see his face I am certain i could place him and his house. As it stands he does seem familiar but I can not tell from where. At any rate he appears to be a foe of the Fire Hags which makes him good enough in my book. Why do you ask?&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Oh I had the same difficulty, I thought I knew of all the houses here but that one was unfamiliar, even my uncle mentioned little of him. I had thought that one who had been around neriak longer than I might be able to answer this question for me but it seems we share the same puzzle.&quot; Kyri answered.<br>
<br>
  At that Ayon'daro took his leave of Kyri and mingled elsewhere, lest some see the two speaking overmuch and think some sort of alliance was in the works. The rest of the night was uneventful a few folk spoke of the masked stranger in the halls, but none had a clue who he was or which side he was on. Eventually the guests departed and Kyri was again alone with Nystyre.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Well I suppose I'll need this guise again for the actural ascension. Perhaps my good looks won't frighten him as much next time.&quot; Kyri mused after she passed along the tidbits of gossip she had picked up on.<br>
<br>
   &quot;A different dress of course&quot; Nystyre replied &quot; a lady of House D'vir would not be caught wearing the same dress twice to any formal gathering. But yes, this Waes'Harventhar does need watching, one who would take such pride in a whispered mention of his fallen house's name would certainly wish to make their mark here. It will be interesting to see what his next move shall be. But until then we shall continue to watch.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Soon after Kyri made her way from the estate, back in the comfort of her own gear, all that pampering in the estate would make her soft and vulnerable if she had to deal with it on a regular basis. <br>
<br>
   But the question of Maelgroth still remained. She was holding out on D'vir as it stood. Nothing had been said to him of the old woman or the priestess as yet. Plus Maelgroth seemed to panic when she approached him at the party. Was he lacking nerve? In over his head perhaps? Using magic to leave was a bit overdoing things, he might be less confident than she had first thought, thus the mask? To hide his fears?<br>
<br>
  Better to wait a bit longer, she decided, let him make his next play and see how it turns out. If his fear was a sign of weakness then he'll be devoured by his foes, if it was a temporary lapse then there is still hope for him. Still a helpful hint or two might be in order.<br>
<br>
   The next day Naelaelayle found a note in their old shack in the Foreign Quarter, as she still visited the old place from time to time to keep up the appearance of habitation to any watching eyes. It was sealed in wax but no house emblem was seen. A name was on the outside. Maelgroth.<br>
<br>
    Returning quickly to their quarters in the League halls, she gave the note to Maelgroth who openned it and read the brief note inside as a platinum coin fell to the floor as the note was openned.<br>
<br>
   &quot;A truth seeker can almost see the truth through the mask. Caution in word and deed might be prudent. A great house watches and waits but its chief eyes lay in the Shadows. Time has been bought, and further assistance might be given.&quot;<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maelgroth>Maelgroth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/18/03 1:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1> <br>
It did not take long for Maelgroth to decipher the message. Discrete inquiries resulted in the identity of the author being revealed.<br>
<br>
“Tell me brother, what do you know of Kyri?” Maelgroth asked his brother Malingrad, they were meeting in the old shack where the note had first been found.<br>
<br>
“She is a talented assassin.” Malingrad replied carefully. Was his brother preparing to replace him after his failure at house security.<br>
<br>
“Better than you?”<br>
<br>
“Her skills are becoming legendary, as is her unusual devotion to platinum.”<br>
<br>
“So she is a mercenary?” the young necromancer growled.<br>
<br>
“Hardly, though she does work for pay, she is quite selective, from what I hear.” Malingrad was watching his brother closely, he had grown in power very quickly and the rogue doubted he would survive a fight with his younger half brother. “Would you like me to seek her out?”<br>
<br>
“I don’t think your services will be necessary for this task, I have another mission for you, one more suited for your skills. It is time we prepare to move against House Sol’Calar (the Eye Eaters). As you know they live in 2nd gate inside our first ancestral home. They are a quiet house, rarely taking part in vendetta and politics.” Maelgroth carefully handed a scroll case to Malingrad.<br>
<br>
“Inside are the original blueprints to the house. I am sure there have been some changes, but perhaps a few of our secrets remain undiscovered. Scout out this house and return with information concerning their security.”<br>
<br>
“I will obey.” Malingrad replied in the old tongue. He was sure he was being sent to his death. The mission was too easy. As he stood up to leave his brother called out to him.<br>
<br>
“Be careful, we are close to our goal.”<br>
<br>
After his brother left, Maelgroth gated back to his quarters.<br>
<br>
“I have sent Malingrad to scout the Sol’Calar. That should keep him busy.” <br>
<br>
“Good, tell me more of this Vynna K’yari.” His mother chirped.<br>
<br>
She had not stopped chittering about how a cousin of mighty hose D’Vir had taken an interest in her son. Maelgroth was beginning to regret asking her advice on this matter, especially in light of recent events. He could tell the old woman was dying to gossip with someone about the doings of her house, they were so close and she had waited a very long time.<br>
<br>
“I am more concerned with our vengeance, there will be time for alliances after our victory.”<br>
<br>
“Of course you are right.” She conceded. “You have a task for me?”<br>
<br>
“The Fire Hags are loosing too quickly, the Ragar’Golhyrr are too strong for them.” Maelgroth began. This was a dangerous and risky mission. “I need you to get a carriage, similar to those used by House D’Vir and I need you to arrange an incident.”<br>
<br>
“A bold move.” Naelaelayle replied. “Do you intend to duplicate the blazon of house D’Vir as well?”<br>
<br>
“It won’t be necessary, we won’t be angering House D’Vir.”<br>
<br>
“I will have things arranged in a few hours.” His mother said, leaving the room.<br>
<br>
As soon as he was alone, he cloaked himself in shadow and headed upstairs. It was with some trepidation he approached her door.<br>
<br>
The door opened before he could knock.<br>
<br>
“Kyri?” Maelgroth whispered. The room was dark, but with his vision he could see the table and chairs as well as the battered targets on the wall, many still with throwing knives sunk into their centers.<br>
<br>
“Took you long enough.” A voice whispered back, from behind him.<br>
<br>
“Well, I have been busy, Vynna K’yari.”<br>
<br>
“If we continue to call each other by our aliases we will be standing in the hall all night, won’t you come in, we have much to discuss.”<br>
<br>
As he shuffled carefully into the room he saw, Kyri pop into view in one of the chairs, somehow she had ghosted past him as he passed through the doorway. He noticed she took the chair farthest from the door, it also had its back to the wall.<br>
<br>
“I have disarmed the traps you are most likely to trip, don’t do anything unexpected and you will be fine.”<br>
<br>
“So, which of us is caught up in the other’s business?” Maelgroth began, cutting directly to the reason he had come. “Are you working an angle with House D’Vir? If so I will not tip your hand.”<br>
<br>
“There is no angle with that one, at this time. He merely asked me to make some inquiries as to the identity of a certain house guest.”<br>
<br>
Malegroth had grown up in the alleyways of the foreign quarter. He knew what was coming next. “So, how much does he know, and how much do you want?”<br>
<br>
“He knows your house is attempting to make a comeback, he knows you were behind the fall of Vlos’Shannaal and he suspects your hand in the war between the Chath’elg’Caress and the Ragar’Golhyrr.”<br>
<br>
“Who else knows?”<br>
<br>
“I have told no one else.” She could see the necromancer considering his options. He could attempt to silence her permanently. That was the least likely and possible. He could attempt to bribe her, but he must know there is no way his house could compete against the coffers of house D’Vir. Or he could simply ignore the matter.<br>
<br>
“So what do you want?” He asked again.<br>
<br>
“I don’t really know, at the moment I am enjoying my view of events. I will have to share some additional information with Nystyre soon.”<br>
<br>
“I am sure you will, what does he know about you?”<br>
<br>
‘Nice try, kid.’ Kyri thought to herself. “He knows more than you would think.”<br>
<br>
“As you know we are a poor house, with little to offer at the moment.”<br>
<br>
“Indeed.” She agreed, curious to see what he would come up with. A promise of future support would be valuable, but had no tangible value at the moment.<br>
<br>
“What would you say if we were to offer you the chance to examine, up close, and under supervision the workings of a greater house vault?”<br>
<br>
Kyri had been itching to get the chance to look at one for years, and seeing the Waes’Harventhar vault in the shack those many months ago had only whetted her appetite.<br>
<br>
“Under supervision eh?”<br>
<br>
“There is no other way for me to vouch for your safety. My mother will know if anything goes missing and, as you know the chest is sentient after a fashion.” Maelgroth knew he had her interest.<br>
<br>
“Well it is a relic of a bygone era, it might be worth looking at for novelty reasons.” Kyri smiled, the chance to spend some time studying one of these legendary chests, why the knowledge gained from such a visit would be invaluable. Sure there were few such chests left, but all were considered to be nearly impregnable.<br>
<br>
Now it was Maelgroth’s turn to smile.<br>
<br>
‘Nicely played.’ Kyri thought. Now she was going to offer something of value. “What do you want?”<br>
<br>
“I suppose it would be ok if you told Nystyre a bit more, perhaps something about my membership in the lodge of the dead, possibly my presence within the League and if you must my name.” Maelgroth replied carefully.<br>
<br>
“Yes, that’s really nothing, what do you really want?”<br>
<br>
“You can assist me tonight in our vendetta, it will be a small thing, easily done by one with your skills and present you with nearly no risk.”<br>
<br>
“Tell me more...”<br>
<br>
That evening….<br>
<br>
<br>
“I can’t believe I let him talk me into this!” Kyri hissed as she slithered out of the exquisite dress Nystyre had given her for the evening ascension. The equipment she had selected for this caper she had not worn in years, but she was glad it still fit. She had stashed the gear on the borders of the D’Vir manse and then submitted to an hour of pampering at the hands of Vil’Kev’s assistants. She had promised Nystyre she would have some information for him after the party, already the carriages bearing the D’Vir house crest and crewed by animated skeletons would be prowling the city collecting the guests for the affair. She would have to hurry.<br>
<br>
Maelgroth and Jabaner sat a few blocks away from the Ragar’Golhyrr manse, the carriage was a perfect match of the ornate teak carriages used by house D’Vir. It did not bear the all seeing eye crest of that house, instead it was decorated with the severed heads of  Chath’elg’Caress members. <br>
<br>
“Where did you get these?” Kyri whispered.<br>
<br>
“They are trophies of Malingrad’s.” Maelgroth replied distractedly.<br>
<br>
“He works for you?” Kyri giggled, suddenly understanding the attitude of the young rogue she had seen some time back at the Ebon Mask.<br>
<br>
“He is a member of our house.” Maelgroth laughed. “Ok, we only get one chance at this so we have to make it look good. Remember Kill Jabaner here not me!”<br>
<br>
“Not a problem.”<br>
<br>
Maelgroth cast a spell and the flesh melted away from his bones, leaving a giggling skeleton, nearly identical to the one standing next to him.<br>
<br>
“Problem.”<br>
<br>
“I will be driving, Jabaner will be hanging onto the back.” Maelgroth replied, climbing into his position on the coach. The other skeleton followed, climbing onto the place usually occupied by the footman. With a clatter the carriage took off for the Ragar’Golhyrr manse. Kyri trotted along, hidden in the shadows, awaiting her moment.<br>
<br>
As the carriage approached the front gates the guards recognized the carriage, they had been waiting for it, and saw what they expected to see, they cheered their delight as they opened the gate when they was the heads decorating the sides.<br>
<br>
“You will Pay for your Treachery!” Kyri hissed, blossoming out of the shadows and striking at Jabaner. She deliberately pulled her blows to give the skeleton a chance to fight back. She clambered onto the back of the carriage, still trading blows with the skeleton and attempted to force her way inside. Maelgroth quickened the pace and the horses galloped towards the mansion. The gate guards rushed to intercept the assassin.<br>
<br>
“Look out, the Chath’elg’Caress attack!” one shouted striking an ineffectual blow at Kyri who paused a moment to finish off Jabaner before vanishing once again into the shadows.<br>
“Damn assassins, don’t have the guts to face a real fighter!” another hissed, sheathing his sword and allowing the carriage to pass.<br>
<br>
Lord Ayon’daro watched the altercation carefully, he wondered at first why the Fire Hags would be so desperate to attack one of D’Vir’s carriages, when he saw the decorations, suddenly he understood. He snickered to himself as he strode out the front gate and slipped into the carriage. His house must be doing better than he thought if one of the great houses was publicly allying themselves.<br>
<br>
As they passed through the outer gates of his manor he waved to his guards. ‘Those men should get a bonus for driving off that assassin.’ He thought. As they took the road towards the Temple of Innoruuk he thought how nice it would be to arrive at the D’Vir manse in a carriage decorated with the heads of his enemies. Why he even recognized a few of them.<br>
<br>
The thought jarred him. He had paid for the deaths of most of the decorations on the cart. There was no way house D’Vir would take contracts like a common assassin. Something was wrong. Hurriedly he looked around, no where was the blazon of the D’Vir visible.<br>
<br>
“Driver, Stop the Carriage Now!” Ayon’daro shouted.<br>
<br>
The vehicle sped up, now it was racing along the road, he could see the temple approaching across its moat. He could hear chanting coming from the driver’s compartment.<br>
<br>
“You won’t catch me that easily! He screamed. With a series of powerful kicks he broke the door and leapt out, aiming for the moat, it was deep and would protect him from being crushed on the road.<br>
<br>
He landed with a titanic splash, the impact literally drove him to the bottom. He had nothing to worry about, he was a strong swimmer and close to the temple, he would survive. How typical of the Chath’elg’Caress and desperate.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, he realized he was rooted to the bottom of the moat. He thrashed about wildly desperate to escape, after a while the moved no more.<br>
<br>
The chanting stopped, and the cart moved on, at a more sedate pace, as Lord Ayon'Daro drowned he could see the broken door flapping wildly as the carriage moved away.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tanare>Tanare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 124<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/23/03 8:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Well that was simple enough</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought as she watched the carriage and its occupant move out to his fate. She should really be getting back to the D'vir estate before she was missed. Then again there was that guard's comment as she left that had to be addressed. <br>
<br>
  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Too afraid to face a real guard?&quot; I think not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> she thought to herself. It was annoying to have to fiegn flight before such ill trained guards. Of all the guards only one actually managed to even draw a sword before she had all but gotten into the carriage. Now they will have to be punished for their arrogance, after all she did have her reputation to think of if anyone managed to identify her. Drunken guards boasting of how they drove off Kyri Velkyn would certain lower the asking price of anyone seeking to hire her in the future. So the guards had to be dealt with.<br>
<br>
 There were four in all, the two at the main gate on the outside and two others just inside. The real trouble would be avoiding the bloodshed, after all D'Vir would get a bit suspicious if she returned all splattered in blood. <br>
<br>
  The two at the gate were congratulating themselves on a job well done and not even close to paying attention as they should. The assassin had been driven off and they were the heros of the night. The younger of the two, as Kyri suspected, had been a bit nervous about the prospect of a fight- no doubt why he was banished to exterior duty. So it was only moments before the guard wandered off to the bushes to relieve himself while his partner kept watch. Unfortunately he chose the place where Kyri was hiding, her garrotte itching to be used. Slipping behind him she strangled him as he was unable to call for help and the shaking of the bushes failed to alert his partner, who merely thought the youngster didn't have the stomach for the work and was puking his guts up in the bushes.<br>
<br>
 After the bushes fell silent and the guard failed to return, his companion now grew suspicious and warily made his way to the bush where his partner was last seen. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>If that pup fainted on me i'll have his head.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the veteran thought to himself as he grew near. Suddenly he heard a whistling sound through the air and fell to the ground as the throwing star struck him cleanly in the throat. As he gurgled his life's blood away Kyri slipped out from the other side of the bushes and took some rope out of her packs. <br>
<br>
The inner guards would be checking up on their companions shortly, she knew from her observations earlier before the carriage arrived. So she only had a short time to prepare. Sure enough, a muffled call met by silence brought the openning of the side gate where a third guard stepped outside looking for the two who failed to answer his call. At the sight of the guard lying in a pool of blood near the bushes he made a quick call to within and his partner also stepped outside. The moment he did so a pair of nooses droppeded around both their necks from above where Kyri had balanced herself at the top of the wall while staying out of sight from the other side before she stood and readied the nooses when the second guard was called.<br>
<br>
  Before the guards could react, Kyri leapt off the wall inside the estate holding onto the ropes in each hand. Now while she wasn't heavy enough to drag the guards up the wall while she descended, the suddenness of her action and the the fact she gave herself half the length of the wall additional rope to work with drew the nooses tight around the guards necks and with two sickening cracks, the guards' brief struggles came to an abrupt end as Kyri's weight added by the time spent falling proved to be enough force to break their necks.<br>
<br>
   At the sound of the cracks, Kyri dropped to the ground and slipped out the still open side gate before anyone else could react. Checking the guards she found the two who were hung lying on the ground, their heads at odd angles , as dead as the other two she dispatched only minutes before.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>So much for fear eh?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought to herself as she gazed down at one of the guards at her feet, the one who had made the comment as she left the area after the 'assassination' attempt.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Well NOW I feel better. Guess its time to go back and get a bit more pampering before the ascension. If anyone says anything, well, i just needed some air.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought as she slipped back into the night, making her way to the D'Vir estates. After all this ascension would be one talked about for months to come she was sure. And Kyri had a front row seat for it.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maelgroth>Maelgroth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/25/03 4:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1> There was considerably less attention paid to the masked necromancer on his arrival this evening. Everyone was talking about the bold assassination of lord Ayon’daro. Nystyre was in the corner speaking earnestly to several other house members.  The young necromancer directly approached the group.<br>
<br>
“I have some additional information about the attack on the Chath’elg’Caress.”<br>
<br>
“Speak quickly, we must redress this affront to our house immediately!” En’garoth Firehand hissed. He was the house wizard and a renowned duelist in his own right.<br>
<br>
“We would do better to speak of this matter privately.”<br>
<br>
En’garoth gestured and the small group appeared in the head of the house’s quarters.<br>
<br>
Suddenly Maelgroth felt very alone.<br>
<br>
“There is no slight on your house. Ayon’daro foolishly got into the wrong carriage.” He began. “Even there he would have been safe, no harm would come to him on a journey to your house, regardless of how he arrived.”<br>
<br>
“It was not the fire hags.” Nystyre announced.<br>
<br>
“I would not look too closely at the details of this action, we shall make our claim on the souls of the Chath’elg’Caress and the Ragar’Golhyrr public soon.” <br>
<br>
“You will do so immediately!” En’garoth howled.<br>
<br>
“Don’t make the mistake the Vlos’Shannaal made in their dealings with us!” Mael replied coldly. Even if he died this night his house would be remembered. He continued more quietly. “Ayon’daro was only killed after he left our carriage, if he refuses our hospitality, we cannot ensure his safety.”<br>
<br>
Nystyre began to chuckly dryly.<br>
<br>
“There is another reason why your investigation should not be too aggressive, and why you should encourage others to ignore this matter.” He continued.<br>
<br>
Maelgroth could hear the sounds of the party somewhere else in the manse, it was a distant murmur like a small stream hidden in a thick forest.<br>
<br>
“Your house could be implicated if the search were thorough enough.” <br>
<br>
“Explain!” En’garoth ordered.<br>
<br>
“It’s not necessary, I know what he speaks of.” Nystyre replied.<br>
<br>
“Let me assure you, the deaths of the guards was no part of my plan. The link is tenuous and the only houses that might work hard enough to find it are soon to be lost anyway.” Maelgroth replied.<br>
<br>
“That is not good enough.” The wizard hissed, now more angry at not having an enemy to kill than at the imagined slight to his house.<br>
<br>
“It will have to be, I imagine a certain organization would take issue with any actions taken against its membership.” He made the secret sign of the League of Shadows.<br>
<br>
“I doubt they would stand so closely behind one of your years.” En’garoth replied carefully.<br>
<br>
“Perhaps not for me, but most certainly for another.”<br>
<br>
“You are right there.” Nystyre observed wryly.<br>
<br>
“Finally, to demonstrate my wish for continued good relations between our houses I will place myself entirely in your hands.” Maelgroth removed his mask.<br>
<br>
The elders of house D’Vir, excepting its Scion, laughed with delight at the young face behind the mask.<br>
<br>
“My true name is Maelgroth Waes’Harventhar.”<br>
<br>
The elders immediately stopped laughing.<br>
<br>
Nystyre and Maelgroth took up the laughter as it dropped off from the startled elders.<br>
<br>
“This has indeed been a rare evening’s entertainment.” En’garoth replied, recovering from his initial shock. “You indeed have the look of your parent’s about you, still appearances can be faked, it is your houses legacy that has value.”<br>
<br>
“I thank you for the compliment.”<br>
<br>
“How do we know we have more than a single individual standing before us, possessing only what he could glean from the League’s vault and scavenge from the ruins of Kunark.” En’garoth finished carefully.<br>
<br>
Maelgroth was totally at a loss on how to respond. Fortunately Nystyre was able to provide the answer.<br>
<br>
“Take this in your hand and tell me the Waes’Harventhars have lost their touch.” The powerful necromancer handed his chief wizard the Feir’Dal skin reply sent to him many months ago. It was still warm, pulsing with a life of its own.<br>
<br>
“You have known for so long?” the wizard muttered. <br>
<br>
“Suspected at first, true certainty came tonight.”<br>
<br>
“We would assume that your agent’s actions, which forced us before you, meet the requirements you set?” Maelgroth asked carefully replacing his mask and slipping back into the old tongue.<br>
<br>
“That one has exceeded our expectations, despite certain difficulties that present themselves from those actions, we are well pleased.” Nystyre replied in the same tongue gesturing towards the door.<br>
<br>
“I suppose I should give my regards to Athava, after all it is her Ascension day.” Maelgroth replied exiting the room.<br>
<br>
After the young Teir’Dal left, En’garoth turned to his lord. “He has certainly tied us up in a nice bow. What would you have us do?”<br>
<br>
“Let the game play out.”<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maelgroth>Maelgroth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/30/03 4:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1> <br>
A servant was waiting outside the door to guide Maelgroth back to the party. As he followed the young Teir’Dal manservant through the manse he sighed in frustration. It would take many lifetimes to assemble the wealth and influence that the D’Vir possessed. Still, it would not be long before there was only one house left. The servant stopped and opened a set of double doors, he was back at the ascension.<br>
<br>
Kyri was relieved to see Maelgroth appear at the party, but more than a little concerned to notice that he had come from Nystyre’s quarters. Could the pup be attempting treachery? She thought about that for a moment and finally decided that someone who had played the game so well for so long would not make such a foolish mistake so close to the endgame. Still, perhaps she should check out the lay of the land before making her presence known to him. A gaggle of maidens frolicked past her, she used them for cover and ghosted over towards the bar.<br>
<br>
The party was well planned, the food was perfect as was the entertainment. Maelgroth allowed himself to enjoy the festivities, mingling freely with the crowd.<br>
<br>
“Jindrun’Belbol?” A quiet voice asked from behind Maelgroth.<br>
<br>
“You have found us.” He said, turning about, expecting to see Kyri at last. Instead there was a young Teir’Dal maiden standing there. She was wearing a mask made of spiderling silk, in fact a significant number of youngsters were wearing masks, it appeared the old fashion was making a comeback. In this case the silken mesh was so fine he could easily make out the features behind it. She was beautiful.<br>
<br>
“It seems you might have been expecting someone else?” came the reply, amusement and disappointment resonant in her tone.<br>
<br>
“Perhaps, but an unexpected guest often times brings the greatest delight.” Maelgroth chuckled, resorting to one of his mother’s favorite sayings.<br>
<br>
“You can call me Chal’zur’Khel (Serpent Body).”<br>
<br>
“As you wish, young one.” In reality she must have been only a few seasons his junior. His experienced eye took in new details. Power flickered in a cold aura about her, she was a necromancer and she was breathtakingly beautiful. “Are you among the guests this evening?” He asked eager for more information.<br>
<br>
“I am.” She said with an excited giggle. <br>
<br>
Her response told Maelgroth a great deal, first that she was un-married since she had not responded in the plural, and also that her house was not allied with the D’Vir.<br>
<br>
“Well, that is most interesting, I don’t suppose your matron sent you here unescorted?” He looked about the room for her bodyguard, unmarried maidens of high houses might be free to do as they pleased on their own time, but at formal affairs tradition dictated an honorguard.<br>
<br>
“My house takes little notice of the affairs of others, being too engrossed in research.” She said dismissively.<br>
<br>
“You mean you snuck out to attend the party with your friends?” He could see her skin darken behind the spiderling mask, she was blushing furiously.<br>
<br>
“Who do you think will win the war?” Chal asked, eager to change the subject. The bold murder of Lord Ayon’daro seemed to balance the scales between the Chath’elg’Caress and the Ragar’Golhyrr.<br>
<br>
“Neither will win.”<br>
<br>
Chal listened to the grim certainty that accompanied that statement and knew that she had found a man who possessed the two qualities she admired most, a mind of his own and the ability to ruthlessly calculate house politics.<br>
<br>
“You seem sure…” She wheedled, taking his arm in hers and leading him off towards the bar. Surely he would have to take off his mask to drink. She could tell by the way he walked that he knew how to handle himself despite lacking the powerful build of a shadow knight or warrior.<br>
<br>
Maelgroth was about to reply with some additional information about the war, but stopped himself at the last moment. As they wended through the crowd, he thought he caught a glimpse of Kyri, but it was hard to tell, she was wearing a different dress and was surrounded by admirers.<br>
<br>
“It seems to us that both houses are now evenly matched, the stalemate could continue indefinitely.”<br>
<br>
Suddenly, a loud boom rattled its way through the ballroom. The noise had come from outside.<br>
<br>
“The Chath’elg’Caress and the Ragar’Golhyrr are battling in the street!” one of the D’Vir footmen shouted.<br>
<br>
Quickly people headed towards the front of the room and the elaborately manicured courtyard that led outside. Chal scurried out the front door with an excited squeal, eager to see some blood shed. Mael followed her.<br>
<br>
Once they were outside, and beyond the shielding that protected the D’Vir manse itself the crackle of eldritch magics filled the air. Allready bodies were littering the street. It appeared both sides had miscalculated. The Fire Hags had summoned their strength, hoping to defeat the Ragar’Golhyrr before they recovered from the death of Ayon’daro. The Truth Finders, angered at the death of their leader had emptied their manor eager for revenge. Both houses had committed all their resources to an assault on the other’s fortified manor, they had run into each other in front of the D’Vir manse. Both houses were trapped. Neither could yield or flee the field before their peers without a total loss of face. This would be a fight to the finish.<br>
<br>
“A wise woman would cloak herself at a moment like this.” Maelgroth whispered into Chal’s delicate ear. She smelled like vanilla.<br>
<br>
“Of course, can you see to my safety?” She replied, her eyes flickered with power for a moment then she faded from normal view.<br>
<br>
“So long as you have no ties to either of these houses, I will do my best.” He said, viewing her invisible form with his eyes of the dead. He also wrapped his body in shadow and faded away.<br>
<br>
The pair watched the fight carefully, it was like a choreographed dance, tonight there were no mercenaries, no hired mages, all members of both houses participated in the battle from the least to the greatest.<br>
<br>
Chal shuddered with excitement as four Chath’elg’Caress warriors dragged a Ragar’Golhyrr noble from his horse and butchered him in the street like a pig. An instant later they were slain by an Ice comet.<br>
<br>
The slaughter continued for an hour, blood pooled steaming in the streets, seeping from the shattered corpses. The cries of the wounded were quickly silenced as they revealed themselves to their enemies. The odor of burnt flesh filled the cavern. At some point during that time Maelgroth and Chal began holding hands, it was one of the most romantic moments in his life.<br>
