<br>
The master of protocol, Vilkev, announced his arrival with the same ringing yet un-emotional tones that he had announced all the other returning guests to the Ascension. It might be one of the most dramatic and bloody nights in recent memory but the D’Vir would carry on as if the bloody battle in front of their gates was a part of the entertainment.<br>
<br>
He looked for Chal, but found another instead.<br>
<br>
“We need to talk.” Kyri whispered, gliding into his sight in a flawless dress. <br>
<br>
“Indeed we do.” Maelgroth replied grimly.<br>
<br>
Surprised at the cold attitude of the necromancer Kyri led him to a quiet alcove without comment. Once safely within the embrace of the alcove they began to talk in earnest. Still Kyri changed her body language to suit that of a young maiden sizing up a potential suitor, no one could hear what was said but a lot could be guessed, two guests hissing at each other in an alcove would certainly attract more attention than a pair of youngsters flirting.<br>
<br>
“I have spoken with D’Vir, he pressed me hard about information concerning our relationship.” Her face was hard and un-emotional, much like the mask Maelgroth wore, her back was to the crowd of guests, they saw a giggling bouncing maiden.<br>
<br>
“He knows more than you think, your action at the Ragar’Golhyrr manse against their guards has potentially drawn the D’Vir into the war of houses, especially since Vynna K’yari could be linked with the death of those guards.” Maelgroth hissed, he had picked up on Kyri’s ruse and his body language was of a male pleading for some “private time.”<br>
<br>
“What have you told him?” Her voice was like flint, the smile like summer wine.<br>
<br>
“I have revealed myself to him and to his top aids. I have also told him of our link through the league…” He watched Kyri’s hand slide unconsciously towards her hip, looking for her trusty dagger. Suddenly he was glad they were in a setting where such accoutrements were out of place. Realizing she could possibly kill him before he could react with some hidden weapon he pressed on. “I have assured him that I have no interest in entangling my houses vengeance with his, nor did I encourage you to take the actions you took.” He watched the hand leave her hip and slide to his shoulder.<br>
<br>
“You tread very dangerous ground.” Kyri growled, her hand found a delicate cluster of nerves between the necromancer’s neck and ear. From a distance her touch appeared gentle, but fingers trained in long hours of lock picking and pickpocketing were deceptively strong. Her grip would make a warrior weep with pain.<br>
<br>
“So do you.” Maelgroth replied icily, the pain in his neck was quite bracing, he was sure it would be quite impressive to someone who was not so deeply in league with the dead. To a powerful necromancer who made a living killing himself by inches in exchange for power, physical pain was something long vanquished.<br>
<br>
“Where do we go from here?” Kyri replied, relinquishing her grip, her fingers were getting sore, the gouge marks on Maelgroth’s neck were quite deep, and obviously ineffectual. “I am committed to staying close to you, to learn your secrets now.”<br>
<br>
“Well, it looks like D’Vir is going to pay you to work for me then.” He laughed, for the first time since his return. “I believe he favors our cause, at least indirectly, he could have ordered you off the job.”<br>
<br>
“What’s next then?” <br>
<br>
“I will have business very soon in Third Gate, a mutual acquaintance of ours has retired there, my house will be paying her a visit soon.” Mael chuckled.<br>
<br>
Kyri suddenly realized how valuable a position the Waes’Harventhars occupied, nearly all the noble houses were blind when it came to Third Gate, the less they thought about it the better. The very survival of this exiled house, under the very noses if its enemies attested to this lack of vision. No one could move about the foreign quarter more easily and without comment than someone who had been there for a century, newcomers would stand out. Mael’s contacts in Third Gate might even rival her own.<br>
<br>
“Anything else, you care to share?”<br>
<br>
“Not at this time, but we should speak again soon.” He replied, watching her saunter away from the alcove.<br>
<br>
“And Here I Thought You Only Had Eyes For ME!” Chal hissed, storming past him with a sour look.<br>
<br>
Suddenly Maelgroth realized this evening could not come to a close quickly enough.<br>
