<br>
The tables at the D’Vir manse had literally groaned under the weight of the gifts for the ascension, a good portion of which she was sure would go towards the upkeep of a certain heretofore unknown niece from Mistmoore. Indeed, there was much the ebon mask in general and Kyri in particular would gain from these long months of work. <br>
<br>
Naelaelayle and Maelgroth reached their old shack in third gate without incident. Malingrad was waiting impatiently.<br>
<br>
“It took you long enough,” Malingrad hissed, “She is lurking amongst the trolls, as if that would keep her invisible.”<br>
<br>
“It is as I expected.” The necromancer replied calmly. He stared at his brother, such behavior was not acceptable. His mother seemed not to notice his step brother’s lack of respect.<br>
<br>
“You will assist your mother against the dregs of the Ragar’Golhyrr.” He said finally, when the silence had stretched on for an uncomfortable period. “If you survive the assault, I will expect an improved attitude from you Malingrad, I do not have time to properly chastise you now.” Maelgroth growled. He had grown in power and now he easily eclipsed that of his brother the rogue. He had little to fear.<br>
<br>
“Of course, your will is my law,” Malingrad replied in the old tongue. “I apologize for my lack of respect, it has not been long enough to break the habits of a lifetime.” The two, mother and son, slipped from the shack and headed back towards Third Gate, leaving Maelgroth to his business with the Chath’elg’Caress.<br>
<br>
“I will have to work harder if I wish to keep my head.” Malingrad mutterd.<br>
<br>
“Indeed you shall, but not in the way you think.” Naelaelayle muttered.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean?”<br>
<br>
“We were a servant house of the Waes’Harventhars, did you ever think about how we came to that position?” the elderly Teir’Dal snarled.<br>
<br>
“I must admit I have not.” The rogue replied, wondering why his mother had decided to share this information with him now. <br>
<br>
“We were once a noble house in our own right, but we crossed the Waes’Harventhars and as punishment we became their slaves. Long had we plotted their downfall, but we were too slow, others struck before us.” She coughed delicately before continuing. “We have a score to settle with those houses that have forced us to wait for our vengeance. Only through destroying the last of the Waes’Harventhars at the moment of their glory will we reclaim our honor.”<br>
<br>
“So, he is not to be treated with respect?” the rogue chuckled darkly.<br>
<br>
“He is to be treated with all the respect he deserves.” Naelaelayle snickered. “Every day I had to care for that vermin, each sacrifice I had to make, denying my own family food and shelter, training and education in order to prepare for this day. I never forgot who we were. Oh yes, vengeance is coming, we will make those houses that stole our retribution pay first, then the Skinflayer.”<br>
<br>
“I had no idea you were so devious.” Malingrad snorted as they passed the third gate and entered the noble quarter proper.<br>
<br>
‘Neither did I.’ Kyri thought to herself as she ghosted along behind the scheming pair.<br>
<br>
Maelgroth had little trouble finding the sniveling matron of the Chath’elg’Caress, she was crouched in an alley killing rats for money. A tarnished table knife bearing her house crest trembled in her hand.<br>
<br>
“You have fallen far.” Maelgroth proclaimed.<br>
<br>
“Indeed we have, but we shall rise again, great riches can be yours if you aid us now.” The matron pled.<br>
<br>
“I already have all the wealth I require.”<br>
<br>
“We can help you, you can assume our position amongst the great houses, take us into your service, we will serve you well.” She wheedled.<br>
<br>
“I will be assuming a station very soon, one that your house long coveted, a position that took four houses to fill.” The necromancer replied. <br>
<br>
She stared at him uncomprehendingly. <br>
<br>
“It was our hand that turned the Ragar’Golhyrr against you. It was our blade that stripped the skin from your daughter’s face, our vengeance that brought the head of the Truth Finders to his grave. We have been the architects of your downfall.”<br>
<br>
“Why?” the once proud matron whined. All sense of pride and self respect withering away.<br>
<br>
“Think on it, fool, had you half the skill of your forebears you would have figured it out by now, it took four of you to bring us low, since our return we have not hidden ourselves.”<br>
<br>
“You are the one wearing a mask.” The matron snapped, regaining a bit of her former grit.<br>
<br>
“It is time to see the truth.” Maelgroth removed the mask, and grinned at her.<br>
<br>
“Your face, it is familiar to me…surely we have had dealings in the past?” she began. Her eyes widened with shock when she saw the flaying knife in his other hand. <br>
<br>
“Waes’Harventhar…” she gasped in terror as a spell paralyzed her.<br>
<br>
“Indeed, now you will pay for what you did.” Carefully Maelgroth began to peel the skin from the matron’s face, this time he paid special attention to the many muscles that enabled her to smile, to laugh, those along with her tongue would be coming with him. Blood spurted wildly, painting the walls of the alley. This face would be joining another. When he was done, he left the mutilated corpse for the rats, and the trolls.<br>
