<br>
‘You are more right than you suspect.’ His stepmother thought to herself. She hated being so close to her stepson. He had grown in power frighteningly fast, and his skill with needle and flaying knife had finally eclipsed hers. Looking at him was like looking into the eyes of his parents, eyes that still haunted her sleep, eyes she had wished to pluck out of the owner’s skull and pickle in a brine of tears. <br>
<br>
“We shall move against the Sol’Calar soon?” She pleaded, eager to be done with this masquerade. <br>
<br>
“Indeed, we must not delay our vengeance over long.” He replied, carefully arranging the hair so it artfully covered the elaborate stitching that held the face to the tanning rack. <br>
<br>
“Did my half brother survive the night?”<br>
<br>
“He did, and already labors to make good his earlier mistake.” Naelaelayle replied. She did not trust her son to keep their secret longer than he thought necessary. He would remain apart from the clan until it was time for the assault on the last house. <br>
<br>
“It is my right to determine an adequate penalty, see to it that he presents himself to me soon, it will go hard on him if I must seek him out.” The necromancer replied, finally turning from his work. <br>
<br>
“It shall be done as you request.” His step mother replied in the old tongue. The face in the rack was perfect. Already the eyelids twitched with flickering eldritch energies. Soon it would fulfill its proper task.<br>
<br>
“Do we have any proper courting clothes in the vault?” Maelgroth asked hesitantly.<br>
<br>
“Probably, I never thought to look for any.” She replied getting up and shuffling over to the elaborate chest. Carefully she reached out to lift the lid, these things were sentient after a fashion, each time she touched it her loyalty to the Waes’Harventhars was evaluated, she shuddered to think what would happen to her were it to be found wanting. <br>
<br>
It was much harder than usual to coax the chest open this time. <br>
<br>
“Have you found someone suitable?” She muttered, as she sorted through an impressive array of artifacts. The chest would only allow her to remove items that would be of service to the house, some things could be removed easily, others, the most treasured items of the Waes’Harventhars, could only be taken at the express request of the head of the house. There were several items in the chest that would make lesser houses weep with jealousy. Some had once belonged to her own clan, now they only came into her hands at the will of another. Soon that would be rectified… <br>
<br>
Malingrad was watching his sister from the shadows. She was at prayer, reviewing all the indignities visited upon her during her life, hate smoldered in her eyes like lava, thick and heavy.<br>
<br>
He was unsure whether to share his new information with her. She had been punished by their half brother and no doubt would harbor a grudge of impressive proportions against him, but she was at heart one who followed, not one who led. He felt sure she would support her family when the time came. Bringing her in on the secret would only increase the chances of tipping off their prey. Deceit was never one of her strong points. <br>
<br>
He slipped out of the temple without attracting any attention. He had some business to conclude before the assault on the Sol’Calar. The Ebon Mask would be receiving quite a donation this eve. Poisons quick enough to incapacitate a magic user by blocking access to their mystical energies were not cheap.<br>
<br>
He did not notice the shadow that flitted along at his side. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maelgroth>Maelgroth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 31<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/30/03 8:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1> Maelgroth clutched the note to his chest, it was more than he had hoped, his heart beat wildly in his chest. He had never received such a letter, and it, more than anything else spoke of the benefits to be reaped once his vengeance was complete.<br>
<br>
He looked around his quarters hurriedly, he might have time to see her before the raid on the Sol’Calar. His mother had with some hesitation picked out a rather ornate robe, it was entirely too colorful for his taste, being a vibrant blue, but he paid heed to her comment that the robe would alter its coloring to suit the mood of the wearer. <br>
<br>
‘I had better calm myself before, donning it.’ He thought to himself, it would not do to arrive for a tryst in a vermillion cloak. Carefully he set about preparing himself for the evening. He surrounded himself with protective magics and prepared himself for the battle to come. As his heart cooled he debated showing up at all, meeting Chal before battle would surely cause his concentration to suffer, ultimately he decided that not meeting her would have an even worse effect. <br>
<br>
He donned the garish robe and watched in wonderment as its color changed to a stately grey. Tiny skulls appeared in place of the mithral buttons and another larger one appeared on the back of the robe. This robe would indeed do for a young nobleman of the first gate. He affixed the mask he had worn to all the official functions he had attended in Neriak and strode out of his room.<br>
<br>
“Where do you think you are going?” His step-mother croaked at him. “You know we are slated to assault the Sol’Calar this very eve.”<br>
<br>
For a moment Maelgroth was transported back to his adolescence, when this woman had ruled his life. It took a moment to recover himself. <br>
<br>
“I have a small matter to attend to before the attack. I will meet the rest of the family at the appointed time at the secret entrance to the Eye Eater’s manse.” He replied uneasily, he knew she would not countenance a meeting with a maiden so close to battle. Indeed it was truly foolish. Still he rushed to see her. <br>
<br>
As soon as he was gone Naelaelayle chuckled, she knew a love note when she saw one. He would be an easier target than she hoped. She strode purposefully towards the chest. Tonight she would try to reclaim what was hers.<br>
<br>
She spoke the word of command in a harsh whisper. Nothing happened. She reached out to touch the chest, then stopped herself. She could always open it later, once the last of the Waes’Harventhars was dead, the magic of the vault would be gone. With a snort of disgust she left her quarters and headed towards the rendezvous point. Her dagger was warm against her thigh, the potent venom Malingrad had coated it with, was slowly dissolving the leather sheath, it would do worse to the flesh of her step son. <br>
<br>
Maelgroth cloaked himself in shadow soon after leaving his mother. He had no desire to seem to eager, or to walk into an ambush prepared by the last remainders of the Chath’elg’Caress or the Ragar’Golhyrr. He looked about carefully with the eyes of the dead, aside from a few aspiring rogues in the second gate area he saw noting out of the ordinary. He  hastened to the D’Vir manse.<br>
<br>
This thought gave him pause, could this be an ambush by the D’Vir? Would they prevent him from finishing his vengeance, destroying a rising house before it had a chance to flower? He wondered. After a moment he decided that it would not be in their best interest or their style. Still he would have to be careful. <br>
<br>
Kyri was watching Maelgroth carefully as he made is way across the cobblestoned streets of First Gate, he was obviously alone. She noted with some pride that he had taken the precaution of hiding his presence from the unskilled and that his aura glittered with powerful wards. ‘A fool in love, but no fool in life.’ She thought to herself as she glided out from behind the wall she had stationed herself at. Her skill was great indeed, but only a fool trusted skill alone when a stone wall presented itself.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tanare>Tanare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/1/03 7:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1>  As Kyri watched Maelgroth approach she moved to meet him outside the D'Vir estates. Clad in a hooded robe of some quality- the sort of thing a noblewoman might wear when off to some secret liason to hide her identity from the gossips, she walked into his view and waited for him to approach. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Poor guy, thinking his sweetie is here for him. I supppose he'll be a bit upset when he finds out its me and the girl knows nothing about this. But he's smart enough to understand the reason when i tell him.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought to herself as he neared. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Too bad Malingard wouldn't tip his hand regarding the sister, I hate leaving loose ends that might cause trouble lying around. Still no time to wait or else Maelgroth's step mother might make her move.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
   Keeping her head lowered so Maelgroth could not recognize her right, Kyri waited until he drew near and whispered just loud enough for him to hear. &quot;Greetings Maelgroth, I have news for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
  Recognizing Kyri's voiuce, Maelgroth grew visibly upset before calming himself as he hissed back coolly &quot;What are you doing here? I'm expecting another.&quot;<br>
<br>
  Nodding, as she looked him in the eye Kyri went on, &quot;My apologies for the deception but i needed to ensure that you and you alone came to meet me. A letter from one you are fond of seemed the best method to allay any suspisions towards a solo journey.&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;What suspisions do you mean? You could have sent me a message through the guild halls easily enough, no prying eyes dwell there.&quot; Maelgroth replied, then adding a bit wistfully, &quot;So she knows nothing of this then?&quot;<br>
<br>
    &quot;Yes,&quot; Kyri said quietly, &quot;she knows nothing of the note, in fact i have not seen her since that night. But the guildhouse is not safe, at least for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;Speak plainly, I am in no mood for your games tonight. How is the guild house not safe for me?&quot; Maelgroth demanded.<br>
<br>
   Deciding she may as well not bother to try to soften the blow any Kyri jumped right into the matter. &quot;It is not safe because I heard your step mother, your servant in the halls, speaking to your brother about taking her revenge on the last of the Waes'Harventhar for enslaving her family after some long ago house battle.&quot; Kyri stated firmly. <br>
<br>
     &quot;She has gone along with you because she was jealous that other houses brought yours down denying her the pleasure of it. Now that you are about to reclaim your place, she thinks her time to act against you comes very soon. Your brother is working with her, i haven't been able to tell if the priestess is as well. I trailed your brother to the temple yesterday after i discovered this but he did not make contact with her.&quot;<br>
 <br>
    &quot;D'Vir is aware of this plotting as well, in case you wondered, cause i'm not giving him an excuse to cut me out of this job after all this time. I did suggest he look into which house this was since i'm sure you don't have the entire book of the family history in the Third Gate, not to mention what may have been editted out of what you DID have. He didn't seem to curious though.&quot;<br>
<br>
    &quot;So that's why i needed this ruse to get you alone here. I'd knew you'd be upset when you found out the truth. A straightforward note might mean you would be followed. A young man meeting his would-be lover on the other hand would not arouse anything but perhaps amusement if the note was discovered by your step mother or brother, they'd think that you're seeking out love when you yourself were about to be brought down. If you had a better way of getting this news to you safely i'd be happy to try it next time.&quot; Kyri concluded<br>
<br>
   Maelgroth just stood there silently as he took all this in. His world suddenly going off on an unforseen tangent just as the moment victory was in his grasp. The assault on the Sol'Calar was this very night and now it seemed his allies were anything but that. Kyri leaned back against the walls of the estate and waited for Maelgroth to digest this all. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maelgroth>Maelgroth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/1/03 9:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=804.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Flayer</span><hr size=1> “They plot against me?” The necromancer hissed in shock.<br>
<br>
“Indeed, they have been planning revenge since before the fall of your house.” Kyri replied skeptically. She sensed the hand of the Lord of Hate in this matter, the twists and turns were too abrupt to be anything else. Not for the first time she considered cutting her losses and returning to her vagabond life. Lord Platinum required little in the way of emotion. <br>
<br>
They stood quietly together before the gates of the D’Vir manse, the dead air of the grand cavern was still and quiet. <br>
<br>
“Well, I guess I had better be careful then.” Maelgroth replied with a grin. <br>
<br>
Kyri was suddenly grateful that he was not the sort to punish the messenger for bad news. The smile was cold, as cold as velium and as dazzling. <br>
<br>
“Perhaps you could be of service to me, in a small matter.”<br>
<br>
“Of course.” Kyri replied already thinking of the considerable stock of poisons she had on hand.<br>
<br>
“If I fall, I would not have the treasures of my clan fall into the hands of some degenerate servants. Perhaps you could move the vault to Didi’s quarters, she has taken the lodging of the late Lord Gray, I am sure she has the space.” He began, seeing her look of betrayal, he hastily added, “Should I not return, you may take what action you will, but I would leave you the option of not becoming a target, my mother will be able to track the location of the chest, for at least a little while.”<br>
<br>
“As you wish, Waes’Harventhar.” Kyri replied slipping into shadows. As she flitted away she was calculating how long it would take to reach the league manse, move the chest and return to keep an eye on Maelgroth. She doubted his family would be overhasty in their revenge.<br>
<br>
“It seems many matters will be settled this eve…” Maelgroth mused as he turned towards the Sol’Calar manse, it was in Second Gate, several blocks from the D’Vir manse, and was the ancestral home of the Waes’Harventhars, being their seat of power for many centuries before their rise to the First.<br>
<br>
Many times in his youth he had passed this house, quickly, carefully, mindful of the part its current occupants had played in his current status. It was well kept, and its wards intact, save where the Sol’Calar had failed to detect the old secret door. His eyes of the dead detected his brother and mother lurking in the shadows near the hidden entrance.<br>
<br>
“How was your meeting?” Malingrad leered.<br>
<br>
“More interesting than I had expected, brother.” Malegroth replied.<br>
<br>
“You two can blather on about your conquests after this night is through.” Their mother hissed. She was eager to begin, and her knives kept creeping into her hands, like a cat’s claws lurked in its paw.<br>
<br>
“Where is Bliss?”<br>
<br>
“She shall join us once we enter, she was never one for stealth.” Naelaelayle chuckled.<br>
<br>
“Lets get this business done!” The necromancer growled, summoning a skeletal servant and striding purposefully towards the secret door. It gibbered eagerly at his heels, hungry for the life force of the living. His family followed in his wake.<br>
<br>
It seemed the Sol’Calar had not worked hard at the wards in their new home after the fall of the Waes’Harventhars, their defenses were good, but brittle. Easily breached. They started in the servant’s quarters and found them to be mostly empty, those few servants they encountered were easily and soundlessly slain.<br>
<br>
The second floor proved more of a challenge, Naelaelayle and Malingrad moved like wraiths killing family members as they slept, their knives wept blood on the ornate carpeting, indigo tears patterned the walls as a house silently fell. Malegroth left them to the butchery, and crept forward to the third floor, carefully dispelling wards as he went, though he left a few behind to warn of the approach of his brother, should he get sloppy enough to fail to check for them himself. <br>
<br>
He entered a hallway, festooned with the portraits of Sol’Calar ancestors, they all seemed to be scowling at him as he advanced towards the set of double doors that would lead to the master bedroom. There was a smaller door to his right, obviously for a child, he would leave that to his kin, he had business with the masters of this house and would not be delayed.<br>
<br>
Enchantments crumbled under the bony fists of his servant and in an instant the door was split in two and he stood before the heads of the household.<br>
<br>
Cael Sol’Calar had been the war leader of his house for centuries and careful plotting had led him to the bed chamber and later the marriage altar of the Matron of the Eye Eaters. He was no stranger to house warfare, yet, it had been easy to lapse into that somnambulant state that gripped many of the houses in Neriak. Many times he had debated plans for this very day with his mate I’rsalla, but she had preferred to spend time in her studies of rare plant life than to worry about the distant chance that someone might move against them.<br>
<br>
The Sol’Calar had made a practice of not participating in politics, in fact they had only rolled the bones once, and that time it had paid off, in spades. The fall of the Waes’Harventhars had yielded up many books of lore that had kept I’rsalla entranced for many a year. When no one came within the first decade to claim them by force, her guard slipped a little, now in the tenth decade of the fall of the Skin Takers, ownership of the books had become a moot point, no one was going to claim them.<br>
<br>
The figure standing in the wreckage of their doorway proved their claim was transitory at best.<br>
<br>
I’rsalla squeeled in outrage as the door caved in and began to frantically struggle to recall at least a shred of combat magic.<br>
<br>
Cael took in the measure of his foe at a glance.<br>
<br>
“You shall not have the pleasure of adorning your gates with our faces!” He hissed, drawing his sword. It had been an age since he had needed it, still he had practiced with it regularly. He knew he was well past his prime, but he would deny the Skin Takers their vengeance.<br>
<br>
He swung with all his strength. The blade seemed to be light as a feather, he could almost see it cut the air as it moved. I’rsalla’s eyes met his and understanding flooded into them, understanding and acceptance.<br>
<br>
Her head remained on her torso for a moment, so clean was the cut, then it fell, spilling blood over the ornate bristlesilk sheets from kunark. <br>
<br>
Maelgroth simply stared in shock.<br>
<br>
“You can claim what we have taken from you, but that is all of our’s you shall ever possesses!” Cael roared drawing the hungry blade across his own throat, it drank deeply.<br>
<br>
As the light dimmed from the older Teir’Dal warrior’s eyes, Maelgroth saluted him. He would not desecrate their corpses. He had other matters to attend to.<br>
<br>
He turned to head back downstairs, but saw that his brother and mother had settled their business on the second floor, they were headed towards him all smiles. <br>
<br>
“Is it done?” Malingrad asked eagerly.<br>
<br>
“Nearly.” Maelgroth replied, preparing a spell that would rip the very bones from his brother’s body. His servant waited, its eyes tracking Naelaelayle’s movements.<br>
<br>
“You will Pay for raiding the home of the Sol’Calar!” a small voice hissed, necromantic magic flooded from the small doorway Maelgroth had passed earlier.<br>
<br>
Mael’s concentration was shattered, the voice was Chal’s. <br>
<br>
<br>
